# ============================================================================
# NOTES & SETUP INSTRUCTIONS
# ============================================================================

# 1. SERVICE SETUP
#    Each service should run on localhost and expose its port.
#    For example: `npm run dev` listening on localhost:3000
#
# 2. ADDING NEW SERVICES
#    - Start your service on a unique port (e.g., 3000, 3001, 4000)
#    - Add a new block to this Caddyfile:
#        service-name.chrisesplin.com {
#          reverse_proxy localhost:PORT
#        }
#    - Reload Caddy: `sudo systemctl reload caddy` or `sudo systemctl restart caddy`
#
# 3. HTTPS/TLS
#    - Caddy automatically obtains and renews Let's Encrypt certificates
#    - First access may take a few seconds for cert provisioning
#    - Check /var/log/caddy for issues
#
# 4. TAILSCALE INTEGRATION
#    - Your machine's Tailscale name: quiver-pn54.ts.net
#    - Local Tailscale IP: printed by `tailscale status`
#    - For subdomains to work:
#      Option A: Configure Tailscale MagicDNS to resolve *.chrisesplin.com to this host
#      Option B: Add entries to /etc/hosts on client machines:
#                100.x.x.x app.chrisesplin.com
#                100.x.x.x api.chrisesplin.com
#      Option C: Set up a split-DNS or conditional forwarder in your tailnet
#
# 5. PUBLIC EXPOSURE (Optional - Tailscale Funnel)
#    - To expose a service publicly, add to the service block:
#        @public {
#          header Host service.chrisesplin.com
#        }
#    - Or use Tailscale Funnel: `tailscale funnel 443`
#    - See Tailscale docs for Funnel configuration
#
# 6. FIREWALL
#    - Ensure ports 80 and 443 are open (or just 443 for HTTPS)
#    - Caddy listens on:
#        - 0.0.0.0:80 (HTTP - redirects to HTTPS)
#        - 0.0.0.0:443 (HTTPS)
#
# 7. TESTING
#    - From your Tailscale network:
#        curl https://app.chrisesplin.com --insecure (if DNS not configured)
#        curl https://app.chrisesplin.com (with DNS configured)
#    - Tail logs: `sudo tail -f /var/log/caddy/access.log`
